WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.412 --> 00:00:03.662
(gentle ambient music)

2
00:00:08.100 --> 00:00:11.313
<v Moderator>Dr. Heinrich is returning.</v>

3
00:00:12.270 --> 00:00:17.270
We're going to talk about ADHD, autism,

4
00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:21.557
and something about which I know nothing, OCD.

5
00:00:21.557 --> 00:00:22.470
(Dr. Heinrich chuckling)

6
00:00:22.470 --> 00:00:24.690
Okay, Thomas, take it away, sir. Thank you.

7
00:00:24.690 --> 00:00:27.390
<v ->All right, share that I have nothing to disclose</v>

8
00:00:27.390 --> 00:00:29.130
in regards to these topics.

9
00:00:29.130 --> 00:00:30.150
And what we're gonna talk

10
00:00:30.150 --> 00:00:33.387
about is recognize the characteristics of both ADHD

11
00:00:33.387 --> 00:00:37.110
and autism spectrum disorder, both in adults and children.

12
00:00:37.110 --> 00:00:40.680
We're gonna talk about the management of these conditions,

13
00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:42.960
focused on kind of behavioral therapy,

14
00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:45.300
behavioral modification, as well as psychopharm,

15
00:00:45.300 --> 00:00:46.860
when it's relevant.

16
00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:48.090
Then, we're gonna switch gears

17
00:00:48.090 --> 00:00:50.220
and talk about obsessive compulsive disorder,

18
00:00:50.220 --> 00:00:53.460
both its presentation as well as its treatment.

19
00:00:53.460 --> 00:00:56.130
So I appreciate Dr. Oakley sharing his slides.

20
00:00:56.130 --> 00:00:58.950
So start with a little bit of humor.

21
00:00:58.950 --> 00:01:00.577
It's a quote from Conan O'Brien,

22
00:01:00.577 --> 00:01:03.127
"Just read part of an incredible synopsis of an article

23
00:01:03.127 --> 00:01:06.300
"about attention deficit something or another."

24
00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:08.940
All right, it's funny. I take credit for that.

25
00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:11.550
It's actually from Dr. Oakley, so pretty good, I like that.

26
00:01:11.550 --> 00:01:12.840
And if you haven't found it funny, hopefully,

27
00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:15.660
you'll find it funny by the end of the talk, okay?

28
00:01:15.660 --> 00:01:17.403
All right, so let's talk here.

29
00:01:18.690 --> 00:01:22.260
So an 11-year-old boy is diagnosed with ADHD.

30
00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:24.270
The most common psychiatric comorbidity

31
00:01:24.270 --> 00:01:27.720
in his case would be, A, oppositional defiant disorder;

32
00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:30.960
B, conduct disorder; C, substance use disorder;

33
00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:33.180
or D, learning disability.

34
00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:34.780
And I'll give you guys a chance.

35
00:01:38.130 --> 00:01:41.490
All right, well, let's see where people lie.

36
00:01:41.490 --> 00:01:44.090
It's learning disability, and you guys got it right.

37
00:01:44.970 --> 00:01:48.090
Next one, which of the following would be consistent

38
00:01:48.090 --> 00:01:50.798
with a diagnosis of ADHD?

39
00:01:50.798 --> 00:01:54.150
Hyperactivity and impulsive or inattentive symptoms

40
00:01:54.150 --> 00:01:55.680
before the age of 12;

41
00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:59.490
impairment from symptoms is observed only at school

42
00:01:59.490 --> 00:02:00.900
or grandma's house or daycare

43
00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:04.680
but not at home; a lack of impairment in quality

44
00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:07.620
of social, academic, or occupational functioning;

45
00:02:07.620 --> 00:02:10.953
or six or more criteria present for only three months?

46
00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:17.670
Yep, and the onset before 12,

47
00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:19.850
that's completely correct and we'll get into why some

48
00:02:19.850 --> 00:02:22.980
of the other ones may be wrong as we progress in the talk.

49
00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:25.080
All right, what about the diagnostic criteria?

50
00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:27.600
That's where a lot of those answers kinda come from.

51
00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:30.420
So ADHD is this persistent pattern

52
00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:31.590
in which the patient has

53
00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:34.740
either inattentive and/or hyperactivity

54
00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:36.990
for at least six months.

55
00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:38.280
And this hyperactivity

56
00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:40.260
or impulsivity is inappropriate

57
00:02:40.260 --> 00:02:42.870
for the patient's stage of development.

58
00:02:42.870 --> 00:02:45.900
It's one of the reasons why we don't like diagnosing ADHD

59
00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:49.140
before five because at that development, it's really hard

60
00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:52.690
to discern what's normal development and what's abnormal

61
00:02:53.857 --> 00:02:56.850
from a hyperactivity/impulsivity standpoint.

62
00:02:56.850 --> 00:03:00.660
So these kids or adults need to have the following symptoms,

63
00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:02.580
these cardinal symptoms of inattention.

64
00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:04.170
They need to have six or more.

65
00:03:04.170 --> 00:03:06.360
And if the diagnosis is made in an individual

66
00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:09.600
that's age over 17, it's five or more.

67
00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:14.280
And it's six or more either inattentive and/or hyperactive.

68
00:03:14.280 --> 00:03:18.273
Patients can have both, but it's six or more.

69
00:03:19.110 --> 00:03:21.720
These symptoms, they don't have to meet full criteria,

70
00:03:21.720 --> 00:03:24.120
but these symptoms in hyperactivity

71
00:03:24.120 --> 00:03:28.590
or inattentive, some have to be present before age 12.

72
00:03:28.590 --> 00:03:32.040
And these symptoms cause distress in two or more settings

73
00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:34.740
or impairment in two or more settings,

74
00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:37.860
and they lead to clinically significant distress.

75
00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:40.470
So I'm not gonna go through all of these symptoms.

76
00:03:40.470 --> 00:03:42.210
These are kinda the symptoms that you have

77
00:03:42.210 --> 00:03:46.710
to click that six or five-button

78
00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:48.000
as you kinda go through them.

79
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.910
They're broken up in inattentive and hyperactivity.

80
00:03:50.910 --> 00:03:53.430
You can have either predominantly inattentive,

81
00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:55.200
so they have six of those,

82
00:03:55.200 --> 00:03:58.410
or primarily hyperactive, and they have six of those.

83
00:03:58.410 --> 00:04:00.360
If they have the combined, they have six

84
00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:01.890
of both at least, okay?

85
00:04:01.890 --> 00:04:04.110
So they have both, meet criteria for both.

86
00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:07.353
It's not three and three, it's six and six at a minimum.

87
00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:10.380
So to make the diagnosis, you have

88
00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:14.310
to meet these DSM-V criteria, which we just went over.

89
00:04:14.310 --> 00:04:16.020
Have you guys used a checklist

90
00:04:16.020 --> 00:04:18.420
to help diagnose kids in your practice with this?

91
00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:21.240
You send the checklist home with the parent,

92
00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:23.010
and you instruct them to give it to a couple

93
00:04:23.010 --> 00:04:26.190
of teachers at school or maybe the sitter.

94
00:04:26.190 --> 00:04:29.700
And the tools you use depend on the child's age

95
00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:31.470
as far as, and there's a list there,

96
00:04:31.470 --> 00:04:33.570
and you kinda pick the one based on the child's age

97
00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:35.010
and send that home.

98
00:04:35.010 --> 00:04:37.500
Do you guys use formal neuropsychological testing

99
00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.303
to help diagnose ADHD?

100
00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:43.140
Yeah, I do. And I use it in pretty specific cases.

101
00:04:43.140 --> 00:04:44.670
I see primarily adults,

102
00:04:44.670 --> 00:04:46.740
so I use it in adults that are coming

103
00:04:46.740 --> 00:04:48.240
to me thinking they have ADD,

104
00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:50.370
but it's really hard to piece that history

105
00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:53.160
of prior to 12 having impairment.

106
00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:56.250
I always have kind of the prototypical courses,

107
00:04:56.250 --> 00:04:57.570
I see some medical students

108
00:04:57.570 --> 00:04:59.010
or some college students

109
00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:01.680
that have really prospered throughout grade school

110
00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:03.270
and college and got into medical school,

111
00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:05.340
got a competitive residency,

112
00:05:05.340 --> 00:05:07.863
and now all of a sudden they think they have ADHD.

113
00:05:08.730 --> 00:05:10.350
Where is the impairment prior?

114
00:05:10.350 --> 00:05:11.460
They're pretty high achieving,

115
00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:14.163
so I find testing to be really helpful for this.

116
00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:18.330
And then, one, this was included from Dr. Oakley's slide,

117
00:05:18.330 --> 00:05:19.740
and I've never thought about this,

118
00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:21.900
but in talking to my colleagues,

119
00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:24.960
some have seen people do this is you just trial a patient

120
00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:25.793
on a stimulant.

121
00:05:25.793 --> 00:05:27.960
If they're better, it's ADD.

122
00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:30.153
Don't do that, just so we're aware.

123
00:05:31.740 --> 00:05:33.270
So what does it look like?

124
00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:36.030
Very much like depression, the presentation

125
00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:40.290
of ADHD may change at the individual's level of development.

126
00:05:40.290 --> 00:05:43.080
In childhood, the symptoms are primarily

127
00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:44.643
that of hyperactivity.

128
00:05:46.350 --> 00:05:49.020
And we don't really like to make the diagnosis

129
00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:52.110
of ADHD, again, as I alluded to, prior to ages six

130
00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:53.490
because it's very difficult

131
00:05:53.490 --> 00:05:55.080
to discern what's normal behavioral

132
00:05:55.080 --> 00:05:57.780
and what's abnormal at that stage from a hyperactivity

133
00:05:57.780 --> 00:05:59.070
and inattentive standpoint.

134
00:05:59.070 --> 00:05:59.903
If you look

135
00:05:59.903 --> 00:06:02.250
at those symptoms I just showed you, go to a McDonald's.

136
00:06:02.250 --> 00:06:05.730
You'll see it everywhere.

137
00:06:05.730 --> 00:06:09.090
Adolescents, the presentation tends to change a little bit.

138
00:06:09.090 --> 00:06:11.790
Hyperactivity doesn't become so consistent

139
00:06:11.790 --> 00:06:14.040
or so predominant, rather.

140
00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:17.160
Because, now, the school provides some degree of structure

141
00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:19.710
and limit setting around that hyperactivity.

142
00:06:19.710 --> 00:06:23.820
The inattentive stuff becomes more obvious

143
00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:26.820
because of that structure that's being placed on them.

144
00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:29.190
I'm not saying that the hyperactivity goes away.

145
00:06:29.190 --> 00:06:30.300
There's still fidgeting.

146
00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:32.520
They may describe an inner sense of restlessness.

147
00:06:32.520 --> 00:06:34.950
It's just not nearly as obvious as kids

148
00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:36.750
that are in grade school.

149
00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:38.580
And then, as we get into adulthood,

150
00:06:38.580 --> 00:06:40.440
that same trend continues.

151
00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:42.833
The hyperactivity gets less and less,

152
00:06:42.833 --> 00:06:45.090
and the inattentive can often become more

153
00:06:45.090 --> 00:06:46.980
and more apparent as we're going for.

154
00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:49.320
Again, the hyperactivity doesn't go away,

155
00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:52.323
it just is not as prevalent in the symptom profile.

156
00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:56.130
So what's the epidemiology? This is looking at adults.

157
00:06:56.130 --> 00:06:57.990
And in seeing this slide, I just realized, I forgot

158
00:06:57.990 --> 00:07:00.990
to say what the epidemiology was in children.

159
00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:05.990
For adults, 19 to 45. It's about 2.5% in the population.

160
00:07:06.420 --> 00:07:10.320
For children under six, it's around 2%.

161
00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:13.530
As you go from 6 to 12, it gets up to 9%.

162
00:07:13.530 --> 00:07:17.880
And then, 12 to 17, 12 to 18, it's about 12%.

163
00:07:17.880 --> 00:07:19.350
So what this is telling us

164
00:07:19.350 --> 00:07:22.590
that in adulthood, the numbers drop off.

165
00:07:22.590 --> 00:07:25.080
And that's really consistent with the longitudinal data

166
00:07:25.080 --> 00:07:27.510
that suggests a pretty small minority

167
00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:32.310
of individuals diagnosed with ADHD as a child go on

168
00:07:32.310 --> 00:07:35.160
to have full fledged ADHD as an adult.

169
00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:37.920
And this slide presents that number of about 15%.

170
00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:40.320
I've seen numbers at about 20%.

171
00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:45.320
The good news is a substantial minority, right around 50%,

172
00:07:45.690 --> 00:07:49.293
may have some continued symptoms, but it's primarily,

173
00:07:51.291 --> 00:07:53.790
it's subsyndromal type of ADHD.

174
00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:56.400
But the really good news is a pretty good minority

175
00:07:56.400 --> 00:07:57.900
of them are in remission.

176
00:07:57.900 --> 00:08:00.240
They no longer have the symptoms of ADHD,

177
00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:02.280
so this can be reassuring.

178
00:08:02.280 --> 00:08:03.660
So there seems

179
00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:06.450
to be kind of this growing out within adulthood.

180
00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:08.100
Some continue to have it,

181
00:08:08.100 --> 00:08:10.743
but it tends to mitigate as one gets older.

182
00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:14.430
This is the comorbidity slide.

183
00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:18.270
I expanded this, and that's why the question was wrong.

184
00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:21.510
I did not update the question as I expanded this table.

185
00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:23.460
You can see we kinda break down the comorbidity

186
00:08:23.460 --> 00:08:26.310
and behavioral health conditions.

187
00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:30.690
We can see that oppositional defiant is quite high

188
00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:32.970
at 20 to 30%.

189
00:08:32.970 --> 00:08:36.420
We see depression and anxiety are also quite prevalent.

190
00:08:36.420 --> 00:08:38.370
But it's the learning disabilities,

191
00:08:38.370 --> 00:08:39.870
it's the developmental disorders

192
00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:42.540
that are also very prevalent, specifically learning

193
00:08:42.540 --> 00:08:44.010
and language disorders.

194
00:08:44.010 --> 00:08:45.390
So one of the take-home points is

195
00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:49.200
if you're treating an individual for ADHD in school

196
00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:51.270
and the grades continue to suffer

197
00:08:51.270 --> 00:08:54.300
but the parents are reporting the ADD symptoms are better,

198
00:08:54.300 --> 00:08:56.820
it may be time for some testing at school, looking

199
00:08:56.820 --> 00:08:58.920
for the learning and language disabilities.

200
00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:00.970
And then, other conditions occur as well.

201
00:09:01.980 --> 00:09:03.060
So what do we know?

202
00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:06.240
We know treatment is effective for ADD and ADHD.

203
00:09:06.240 --> 00:09:08.670
We know that early treatment is even better

204
00:09:08.670 --> 00:09:09.600
than later treatment.

205
00:09:09.600 --> 00:09:11.310
We know that treatment is associated

206
00:09:11.310 --> 00:09:13.500
with greater academic achievement.

207
00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:16.740
It's associated with less mood disturbance,

208
00:09:16.740 --> 00:09:20.490
less behavioral problems, less criminal activity,

209
00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:21.690
and less substance abuse.

210
00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:23.860
Interestingly, it's also associated

211
00:09:25.348 --> 00:09:26.850
with less accidents, leading to less TBIs

212
00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:29.130
and motor vehicle accidents in kids.

213
00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:33.600
So the treatment is effective and can really address a lot

214
00:09:33.600 --> 00:09:36.480
of the concerns we have with ADHD.

215
00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:38.730
When I was a resident way back in the day

216
00:09:38.730 --> 00:09:42.180
when Dr. Oakley was starting his teaching,

217
00:09:42.180 --> 00:09:43.680
I was a resident back then,

218
00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:45.570
we learned that the treatment of choice

219
00:09:45.570 --> 00:09:48.960
for ADHD was just stimulants, right?

220
00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:50.130
It's a medication.

221
00:09:50.130 --> 00:09:53.340
Behavioral modification really played no role.

222
00:09:53.340 --> 00:09:55.380
Subsequent studies have really demonstrated

223
00:09:55.380 --> 00:09:58.590
that the optimal treatment is both medication

224
00:09:58.590 --> 00:10:01.020
and behavioral modification.

225
00:10:01.020 --> 00:10:02.700
And we'll talk a little bit about that was,

226
00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:04.530
and this was referring to this landmark study

227
00:10:04.530 --> 00:10:06.840
that demonstrated medications are better

228
00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:08.370
than no treatment alone,

229
00:10:08.370 --> 00:10:11.580
but the combination is better than just psychopharmacology

230
00:10:11.580 --> 00:10:13.350
with a stimulant.

231
00:10:13.350 --> 00:10:16.890
So what are those psychopharmacology choices that we have?

232
00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:18.690
There are two camps.

233
00:10:18.690 --> 00:10:20.430
There are the stimulants and the non-stimulants.

234
00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.320
The non-stimulants are broken down

235
00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:24.810
into the norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors

236
00:10:24.810 --> 00:10:28.770
and the alpha agonists, clonidine and guanfacine.

237
00:10:28.770 --> 00:10:30.450
We know from a stimulant standpoint

238
00:10:30.450 --> 00:10:32.310
that there's two general classes.

239
00:10:32.310 --> 00:10:35.850
You have the methylphenidate and you have the amphetamines.

240
00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:37.230
And at some point during this talk,

241
00:10:37.230 --> 00:10:38.640
I'm gonna say methamphetamines.

242
00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:42.180
That is not a treatment for ADHD, okay? Just not.

243
00:10:42.180 --> 00:10:43.263
But I will say that.

244
00:10:44.190 --> 00:10:45.023
When you look

245
00:10:45.023 --> 00:10:48.000
at the stimulants, there is multiple different formulations.

246
00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:49.830
There's multiple different half-lives,

247
00:10:49.830 --> 00:10:51.660
long-acting, short-acting.

248
00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:53.130
There's different formulations.

249
00:10:53.130 --> 00:10:54.540
There's syrup, there's patches,

250
00:10:54.540 --> 00:10:56.460
there's pills, there's chewables.

251
00:10:56.460 --> 00:10:59.130
And you really pick and choose based on the patient

252
00:10:59.130 --> 00:11:01.440
and what works for them.

253
00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:03.780
And we'll talk about the various roles of stimulants

254
00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:06.750
and non-stimulants kinda going forward.

255
00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:08.280
So how do the stimulants work?

256
00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:11.190
Well, we don't know how they actually address ADHD,

257
00:11:11.190 --> 00:11:14.130
but we know what they are is they increase levels

258
00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:15.813
of norepinephrine and dopamine.

259
00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:18.510
They both do it through the blocking

260
00:11:18.510 --> 00:11:20.340
of the presynaptic channels,

261
00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:24.300
but amphetamines actually have an added bonus

262
00:11:24.300 --> 00:11:26.490
as they push a little bit of dopamine out.

263
00:11:26.490 --> 00:11:28.110
So they have a little bit of push.

264
00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:31.140
And again, these are the first-line treatments

265
00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:34.920
for ADHD, whether for a vast majority of the population

266
00:11:34.920 --> 00:11:38.490
of patients that are presenting with it because they work.

267
00:11:38.490 --> 00:11:41.100
And I'm just showing you some of the effect sizes,

268
00:11:41.100 --> 00:11:43.050
and they're pretty significant for both children

269
00:11:43.050 --> 00:11:45.120
and adolescents and adults.

270
00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:46.200
You kinda see that maybe

271
00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:48.990
that extra dopamine means something given the effect size

272
00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:51.603
of amphetamines being higher than methylphenidate.

273
00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:55.620
The clinicians, when I asked my child psychiatry colleagues

274
00:11:55.620 --> 00:11:56.453
about this, they say

275
00:11:56.453 --> 00:11:58.500
they see pretty much equal responses in both.

276
00:11:58.500 --> 00:12:00.690
It's pretty much dependent on the kid.

277
00:12:00.690 --> 00:12:03.090
Adults, you see a little less efficacy,

278
00:12:03.090 --> 00:12:04.590
compared to children, of stimulants,

279
00:12:04.590 --> 00:12:06.813
but still pretty good results actually.

280
00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:10.530
So stimulants are the first-line treatments,

281
00:12:10.530 --> 00:12:12.570
but they do have side effects.

282
00:12:12.570 --> 00:12:14.610
The side-effect types are similar

283
00:12:14.610 --> 00:12:18.810
between methylphenidate and amphetamines.

284
00:12:18.810 --> 00:12:22.710
However, amphetamines tend to have a higher incidence

285
00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:25.200
of those side effects.

286
00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:27.240
As children are younger, they tend

287
00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:30.810
to have more side effects to stimulants than older children.

288
00:12:30.810 --> 00:12:32.310
So those are a couple take-home points.

289
00:12:32.310 --> 00:12:34.290
The biggest one I always hear about when I talk

290
00:12:34.290 --> 00:12:38.610
to families too are, one, is the lack of appetite,

291
00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:39.690
the appetite suppression.

292
00:12:39.690 --> 00:12:44.070
And that's really real for these kids.

293
00:12:44.070 --> 00:12:46.560
Couple of tricks that I've learned after talking

294
00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:50.100
to my colleagues is really push a big high-calorie breakfast

295
00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:52.560
before their morning pill, okay?

296
00:12:52.560 --> 00:12:54.930
And then, depending on the half-life

297
00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:56.820
of the medication, usually it's worn off

298
00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:58.770
by dinner time, another high-caloric.

299
00:12:58.770 --> 00:13:00.900
I'll tell you, they just don't eat lunch often

300
00:13:00.900 --> 00:13:02.190
because of the appetite suppression,

301
00:13:02.190 --> 00:13:03.570
so you wanna hit the meals.

302
00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:05.610
And then, you have the holidays over the weekends.

303
00:13:05.610 --> 00:13:07.800
If they don't need to attend to stimuli,

304
00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:10.350
if they don't need to really control their hyperactivity

305
00:13:10.350 --> 00:13:13.080
that much, then give 'em a holiday over the weekend

306
00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:15.720
and really push the high-caloric stuff, the high caloric.

307
00:13:15.720 --> 00:13:17.610
And then, the summers are another time for them

308
00:13:17.610 --> 00:13:18.600
to regain their weight

309
00:13:18.600 --> 00:13:21.870
and regain potential growth trajectory.

310
00:13:21.870 --> 00:13:23.610
The other big one is sleep.

311
00:13:23.610 --> 00:13:26.400
That has a lot to do with the half-life of the medication.

312
00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:30.720
But I will tell you ADHD throws off the sleep cycle anyways.

313
00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:32.310
If any of you have ever dealt with somebody

314
00:13:32.310 --> 00:13:35.220
with ADHD, it really makes it hard.

315
00:13:35.220 --> 00:13:39.720
So you really wanna address the sleep hygiene, the CBT

316
00:13:39.720 --> 00:13:41.550
for insomnia aspects.

317
00:13:41.550 --> 00:13:44.190
If you need to go down the route, you change the half-life,

318
00:13:44.190 --> 00:13:46.680
the formulation of the stimulant to a shorter half-life

319
00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:48.060
to see how that goes.

320
00:13:48.060 --> 00:13:50.460
And then, last but not least, you can try a little bit

321
00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:53.073
of melatonin can be efficacious in these patients.

322
00:13:54.420 --> 00:13:57.330
So one of the risk factors on there

323
00:13:57.330 --> 00:14:00.618
that I did not talk about is cardiovascular disease.

324
00:14:00.618 --> 00:14:04.830
The American Heart Association kinda caused a ruckus

325
00:14:04.830 --> 00:14:06.120
when they said that every kid

326
00:14:06.120 --> 00:14:08.430
on a stimulant should have an EKG.

327
00:14:08.430 --> 00:14:10.440
The American Academy of Pediatrics came out

328
00:14:10.440 --> 00:14:12.900
and said not necessary and really left it up

329
00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:15.420
to the clinician, the physician's judgment on whether

330
00:14:15.420 --> 00:14:16.680
to get that or not.

331
00:14:16.680 --> 00:14:17.580
A couple of rules

332
00:14:17.580 --> 00:14:19.980
of when I've seen my colleagues get them is

333
00:14:19.980 --> 00:14:21.990
if there's a family history of cardiac death.

334
00:14:21.990 --> 00:14:24.450
We just learned earlier today about sudden

335
00:14:24.450 --> 00:14:27.330
or long QT syndrome, one of the major reasons

336
00:14:27.330 --> 00:14:30.450
for sudden cardiac death in a younger family member.

337
00:14:30.450 --> 00:14:31.290
That's what you're looking

338
00:14:31.290 --> 00:14:33.264
for when we check an EKG sometimes

339
00:14:33.264 --> 00:14:36.330
for this patient population.

340
00:14:36.330 --> 00:14:38.460
If a patient is complaining of symptoms

341
00:14:38.460 --> 00:14:40.800
that may be related to underlying heart disease such

342
00:14:40.800 --> 00:14:45.000
as palpitations, dizziness, syncope, we check an EKG

343
00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:46.470
before we start a stimulant.

344
00:14:46.470 --> 00:14:50.070
Or if our exam recognizes some cyanosis

345
00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:52.980
or something like that, we would also check an EKG

346
00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:54.900
to make sure, but it's really up to the physician

347
00:14:54.900 --> 00:14:55.953
to make that call.

348
00:14:57.120 --> 00:15:01.050
So when do we look to the non-stimulants?

349
00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:03.390
Okay, again, the stimulants are first line.

350
00:15:03.390 --> 00:15:05.100
When do we look at the second line

351
00:15:05.100 --> 00:15:06.840
without even going to the first line?

352
00:15:06.840 --> 00:15:08.940
Well, sometimes we've done the first line,

353
00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:12.600
and either they haven't reached optimal therapy,

354
00:15:12.600 --> 00:15:15.300
so we wanna add on a non-stimulant to that.

355
00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:17.730
In that case, we usually use the alpha agonist.

356
00:15:17.730 --> 00:15:19.860
Sometimes, patients just don't tolerate.

357
00:15:19.860 --> 00:15:21.210
The side effects are too much.

358
00:15:21.210 --> 00:15:22.770
They're not gaining weight, they're falling

359
00:15:22.770 --> 00:15:24.750
off their growth trajectory.

360
00:15:24.750 --> 00:15:27.510
At that point, we may use one of the non-stimulants.

361
00:15:27.510 --> 00:15:28.560
And I'll tell you,

362
00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:31.290
from an adult practice side, I use non-stimulants

363
00:15:31.290 --> 00:15:32.580
for patients in which I'm concerned

364
00:15:32.580 --> 00:15:36.569
about substance use disorders or a history of that.

365
00:15:36.569 --> 00:15:38.730
And again, there's two classes out there.

366
00:15:38.730 --> 00:15:41.490
There's the norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors.

367
00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:44.910
We have a lot more data on atomoxetine,

368
00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:47.850
I can't even say that, but its effect size,

369
00:15:47.850 --> 00:15:50.580
as you can note, is lower than that of the stimulants

370
00:15:50.580 --> 00:15:51.720
that we just talked about.

371
00:15:51.720 --> 00:15:52.980
So it works,

372
00:15:52.980 --> 00:15:55.710
but there's a reason the stimulants are first line.

373
00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:57.940
It works for both adults and children.

374
00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:01.620
And guanfacine, the alpha agonist, the data exists

375
00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:02.940
for children, but I'll tell you,

376
00:16:02.940 --> 00:16:06.540
I'm having some luck using it in adults as well.

377
00:16:06.540 --> 00:16:08.280
And we'll kinda see, I'm waiting for the studies

378
00:16:08.280 --> 00:16:09.630
to come out in that as well.

379
00:16:09.630 --> 00:16:12.660
There's no reason it shouldn't help in adults.

380
00:16:12.660 --> 00:16:14.190
So we'll hopefully see that.

381
00:16:14.190 --> 00:16:16.190
So this is the clonidine and guanfacine.

382
00:16:17.550 --> 00:16:19.170
And then, there's the behavioral component

383
00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:21.720
that now we're trying to use if at all possible

384
00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:24.330
in children with ADHD.

385
00:16:24.330 --> 00:16:26.760
So this behavioral modification

386
00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:31.260
and just to level set is most effective in kids.

387
00:16:31.260 --> 00:16:33.090
Loses effectiveness in adulthood,

388
00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:35.220
and there isn't a lot of data at all to suggest

389
00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:38.850
that these behavioral modifications can help.

390
00:16:38.850 --> 00:16:40.590
Well, it works a little bit in adolescence,

391
00:16:40.590 --> 00:16:42.570
but very little if anything in adulthood.

392
00:16:42.570 --> 00:16:44.850
And the concept here is, I'm gonna take you back

393
00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:46.650
to psychology 101 in high school

394
00:16:46.650 --> 00:16:49.470
or college, it's operant conditioning, right?

395
00:16:49.470 --> 00:16:51.330
It's positive reinforcement.

396
00:16:51.330 --> 00:16:53.370
If the child is doing something you want

397
00:16:53.370 --> 00:16:55.440
to encourage, you reward them.

398
00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:59.790
If a child with ADHD has handed in their homework on time

399
00:16:59.790 --> 00:17:02.970
for a week, there's a reward that is meaningful

400
00:17:02.970 --> 00:17:05.670
to the child that encourages that type of behavior.

401
00:17:05.670 --> 00:17:07.920
Again, this doesn't occur in isolation,

402
00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:10.140
They have the medication therapy as well,

403
00:17:10.140 --> 00:17:13.380
but the combination is what's most effective.

404
00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:16.560
And these types of behaviors are primarily directed not

405
00:17:16.560 --> 00:17:17.580
at the child.

406
00:17:17.580 --> 00:17:18.420
It's not the child

407
00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:20.550
that's learning the operant, it's the parents,

408
00:17:20.550 --> 00:17:22.710
it's the teachers, it's the school.

409
00:17:22.710 --> 00:17:26.460
Where the child takes home stuff is the routine aspect,

410
00:17:26.460 --> 00:17:29.403
learning to manage a routine and those kind of things.

411
00:17:30.270 --> 00:17:32.283
So that's that contingent behavior.

412
00:17:33.330 --> 00:17:37.140
And for kids that we're kinda questioning the diagnosis,

413
00:17:37.140 --> 00:17:40.200
the five-year-olds, the four-year-olds,

414
00:17:40.200 --> 00:17:42.900
this is first line and actually quite effective

415
00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:44.583
in those patients as well.

416
00:17:45.870 --> 00:17:47.520
All right, for adults, again,

417
00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:49.320
as I mentioned, very little evidence

418
00:17:49.320 --> 00:17:51.750
that the behavioral therapy works.

419
00:17:51.750 --> 00:17:55.080
When I asked my colleague in my clinic who specialized

420
00:17:55.080 --> 00:17:57.600
in adult ADHD, he actually recommended the book.

421
00:17:57.600 --> 00:17:58.440
I haven't read the book.

422
00:17:58.440 --> 00:18:00.960
Has anybody read the book, "Driven to Distraction?"

423
00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:03.000
He said that, that was quite helpful for many

424
00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.030
of his patients to demystify the diagnosis and come up

425
00:18:06.030 --> 00:18:09.840
with some strategies and help to manage the distractions

426
00:18:09.840 --> 00:18:10.950
that they're having.

427
00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:15.300
But the logic comes down to organization, to-do lists,

428
00:18:15.300 --> 00:18:17.760
calendars, utilizing your Outlook on your phone

429
00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:21.153
as much as you possibly can to stay organized.

430
00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:25.380
So these are the behavioral aspects of working with ADHD

431
00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:27.510
as an adult in addition to the pharmacology

432
00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:28.610
that I just mentioned.

433
00:18:31.650 --> 00:18:36.360
So this is a young gentleman, 27-year-old, who has ADHD.

434
00:18:36.360 --> 00:18:39.600
Which of the following will most likely be true in his case?

435
00:18:39.600 --> 00:18:42.300
He's unlikely to have his symptoms confirmed

436
00:18:42.300 --> 00:18:44.520
by his spouse, coworkers, or employer.

437
00:18:44.520 --> 00:18:48.750
He's more likely to be inattentive than hyperactive.

438
00:18:48.750 --> 00:18:51.720
And he's less likely to have a comorbid anxiety disorder

439
00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:54.960
than his age-matched peers without ADHD.

440
00:18:54.960 --> 00:18:58.470
And he's unlikely to have symptoms of ADHD prior

441
00:18:58.470 --> 00:18:59.493
to the age of 12.

442
00:19:05.190 --> 00:19:06.990
And you guys, you got it right.

443
00:19:06.990 --> 00:19:07.823
He's more likely

444
00:19:07.823 --> 00:19:10.500
to be inattentive than hyperactive as his primary.

445
00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:11.820
All the other ones have to do

446
00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:14.010
with the diagnosis requirements.

447
00:19:14.010 --> 00:19:16.650
All right, the optimal treatment.

448
00:19:16.650 --> 00:19:18.270
I've just kinda beat you over the head with this

449
00:19:18.270 --> 00:19:19.103
for a while here.

450
00:19:19.103 --> 00:19:20.550
The optimal treatment for children

451
00:19:20.550 --> 00:19:22.920
with ADHD is medication alone,

452
00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:25.050
medication plus behavioral modification,

453
00:19:25.050 --> 00:19:26.520
behavioral modification alone,

454
00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:29.493
or crossing our fingers and hoping it goes away?

455
00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:37.353
And good. All right, perfect.

456
00:19:39.960 --> 00:19:41.790
All right, let's switch gears.

457
00:19:41.790 --> 00:19:44.430
Let's talk about autism spectrum disorder.

458
00:19:44.430 --> 00:19:48.120
So in 2013, when the DSM-V came out, just

459
00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:50.793
so we're all aware, DSM-V stands for,

460
00:19:51.660 --> 00:19:55.110
or the DSM-V came out and now there's a TR formulation

461
00:19:55.110 --> 00:19:56.100
that came out.

462
00:19:56.100 --> 00:19:57.153
Was it last year?

463
00:19:59.130 --> 00:20:01.350
You know, this is the Bible in psychiatry.

464
00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:05.190
And in 2013, the DSM-V did something fairly dramatic.

465
00:20:05.190 --> 00:20:08.280
They took four diagnoses: Autism disorder,

466
00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:12.540
Asperger's disorder, childhood disintegrative disorder,

467
00:20:12.540 --> 00:20:15.720
which is the most terrifying name of a diagnosis ever.

468
00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:16.593
Is it not?

469
00:20:17.550 --> 00:20:19.230
Just that name, reading that

470
00:20:19.230 --> 00:20:20.760
and having kids just terrified me.

471
00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:21.750
And then, Rett syndrome.

472
00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:22.860
They took all four of those

473
00:20:22.860 --> 00:20:26.250
and rolled them into the autism spectrum disorder.

474
00:20:26.250 --> 00:20:29.340
And that was pretty, pretty intense,

475
00:20:29.340 --> 00:20:31.680
and they got a lot of flashback for that.

476
00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:32.883
But they did that.

477
00:20:33.870 --> 00:20:36.540
And what the autism spectrum disorder is

478
00:20:36.540 --> 00:20:40.740
in the DSM-V is it's a neurodevelopmental disorder

479
00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:44.850
that really is defined by a deficit in one's ability

480
00:20:44.850 --> 00:20:48.060
to socially communicate as well as a propensity

481
00:20:48.060 --> 00:20:52.140
to have restrictive or repetitive behaviors.

482
00:20:52.140 --> 00:20:55.560
And these result in impairment in functioning.

483
00:20:55.560 --> 00:20:59.520
When we think of the social communication impairment, I like

484
00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:01.860
that first box that I have in there, the deficits

485
00:21:01.860 --> 00:21:04.110
in social and emotional reciprocity.

486
00:21:04.110 --> 00:21:06.840
That's it at its core.

487
00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:11.250
That's the give-and-take that occurs in a conversation.

488
00:21:11.250 --> 00:21:13.740
It's one's ability to read when it's appropriate

489
00:21:13.740 --> 00:21:16.860
to say something and when it's appropriate to shut up.

490
00:21:16.860 --> 00:21:20.580
It's appropriate with what to say, much less when

491
00:21:20.580 --> 00:21:21.600
to say something.

492
00:21:21.600 --> 00:21:24.510
And that's often a fundamental deficit in which patients

493
00:21:24.510 --> 00:21:27.480
with autism spectrum disorder have.

494
00:21:27.480 --> 00:21:29.193
The restrictive behaviors,

495
00:21:30.510 --> 00:21:32.790
they can have very repetitive behaviors.

496
00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:35.820
These can be vocalizations.

497
00:21:35.820 --> 00:21:40.740
These can be complex behaviors or just motor movements.

498
00:21:40.740 --> 00:21:44.010
But they can also have very restrictive focuses

499
00:21:44.010 --> 00:21:48.120
on unusual things, trains, car washes, things like that.

500
00:21:48.120 --> 00:21:51.810
And really, all of the conversations revolve around that.

501
00:21:51.810 --> 00:21:53.880
And then, very commonly, especially

502
00:21:53.880 --> 00:21:55.350
in very young children

503
00:21:55.350 --> 00:21:58.500
with autism, it's this hypersensitivity to the environment.

504
00:21:58.500 --> 00:21:59.880
It's either too little stimulation

505
00:21:59.880 --> 00:22:04.293
or too much stimulation can cause them to be quite upset.

506
00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:07.200
So how common is it?

507
00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:08.670
What's really fascinating is

508
00:22:08.670 --> 00:22:11.760
if we look at just simply the age of eight years old

509
00:22:11.760 --> 00:22:15.517
between 2008 when we were dealing with DSM-IV

510
00:22:15.517 --> 00:22:20.100
and 2018 when the new DSM-V came out, we've seen an increase

511
00:22:20.100 --> 00:22:24.660
in autism diagnoses from 1.1 to 2.3,

512
00:22:24.660 --> 00:22:27.360
so a little over two times the rate.

513
00:22:27.360 --> 00:22:29.250
And there could be a couple reasons for that.

514
00:22:29.250 --> 00:22:30.210
Again, I mentioned

515
00:22:30.210 --> 00:22:33.960
that the DSM-V kind of broadened the criteria

516
00:22:33.960 --> 00:22:37.380
for autism spectrum disorders by including all of these.

517
00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:38.850
I think there's that.

518
00:22:38.850 --> 00:22:42.030
I also think that there's more of a general acceptance.

519
00:22:42.030 --> 00:22:44.400
The lay person is more comfortable with the diagnosis

520
00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:46.500
of autism spectrum disorder now.

521
00:22:46.500 --> 00:22:50.160
There are movies and TV shows that have central characters

522
00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:52.020
with this degree of neurodiversity.

523
00:22:52.020 --> 00:22:54.630
And I think that, that's really helped a lot.

524
00:22:54.630 --> 00:22:57.120
But we also now have therapies that we can offer

525
00:22:57.120 --> 00:22:59.100
for patients with autism spectrum disorder

526
00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:00.630
that have a pretty good evidence base,

527
00:23:00.630 --> 00:23:02.700
and we'll talk about that in a bit.

528
00:23:02.700 --> 00:23:04.800
What's really interesting is the gender difference

529
00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:06.720
between autism spectrum disorder.

530
00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:09.660
For example, again, at age eight, boys are three

531
00:23:09.660 --> 00:23:11.700
to four times more likely to be diagnosed

532
00:23:11.700 --> 00:23:13.740
with autism spectrum disorder than girls.

533
00:23:13.740 --> 00:23:14.733
Why is that?

534
00:23:15.630 --> 00:23:17.040
Couple of theories are out there

535
00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:21.093
that girls are just better to mask the symptoms,

536
00:23:21.960 --> 00:23:23.970
and we call that camouflaging.

537
00:23:23.970 --> 00:23:27.450
Some individuals think, diagnostically, we don't pay

538
00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:29.220
as much attention to these symptoms

539
00:23:29.220 --> 00:23:30.930
in girls as we do in boys.

540
00:23:30.930 --> 00:23:33.030
And then, there may be a diagnostic bias

541
00:23:33.030 --> 00:23:35.790
to diagnosing this, either in the tools we use

542
00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:39.600
or the diagnostic criteria leading to more diagnoses

543
00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:41.010
in boys than girls.

544
00:23:41.010 --> 00:23:43.200
So lots to really consider here,

545
00:23:43.200 --> 00:23:46.530
but we're seeing an increased number of patients with this.

546
00:23:46.530 --> 00:23:48.660
So like many behavioral health

547
00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:50.910
and neurodevelopmental conditions, it's a mix

548
00:23:50.910 --> 00:23:54.420
of hereditary factors as well as environmental factors.

549
00:23:54.420 --> 00:23:57.420
Hereditary factors seem to play more of a role

550
00:23:57.420 --> 00:23:59.790
in autism spectrum disorder,

551
00:23:59.790 --> 00:24:01.980
and we have some data for that.

552
00:24:01.980 --> 00:24:06.822
Some of the best data is regarding maternal age.

553
00:24:06.822 --> 00:24:09.660
A maternal age greater than 35 increases the odds rate

554
00:24:09.660 --> 00:24:13.083
of having a child on the autism spectrum by 1.3.

555
00:24:14.130 --> 00:24:18.060
For every 10 years of maternal age past that, there's a 20

556
00:24:18.060 --> 00:24:19.830
to 21% increased rate

557
00:24:19.830 --> 00:24:23.250
of having an autism spectrum disorder patient.

558
00:24:23.250 --> 00:24:25.110
But there's also environmental factors,

559
00:24:25.110 --> 00:24:26.340
and one of the more common

560
00:24:26.340 --> 00:24:29.040
and touchy ones are pharmacotherapy.

561
00:24:29.040 --> 00:24:30.840
We do know, I mentioned valproate

562
00:24:30.840 --> 00:24:33.510
and its teratogenic aspects,

563
00:24:33.510 --> 00:24:35.670
well, it also has the behavioral aspect

564
00:24:35.670 --> 00:24:38.670
of increasing the rate of autism spectrum.

565
00:24:38.670 --> 00:24:40.470
In mothers who are exposed

566
00:24:40.470 --> 00:24:43.047
to valproate during pregnancy, it's 4.4%.

567
00:24:43.920 --> 00:24:46.733
In women who are not exposed, it's 1.5%.

568
00:24:48.120 --> 00:24:50.490
Initially, there were some cohort studies

569
00:24:50.490 --> 00:24:51.630
that raised the concern

570
00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:54.660
that antidepressants, specifically various SSRIs,

571
00:24:54.660 --> 00:24:57.870
are associated with autism spectrum disorder.

572
00:24:57.870 --> 00:25:01.350
Meta-analysis subsequently kinda concluded that,

573
00:25:01.350 --> 00:25:04.380
that increased tick was most likely related

574
00:25:04.380 --> 00:25:05.670
to confounding factors.

575
00:25:05.670 --> 00:25:06.920
And the biggest one being

576
00:25:08.220 --> 00:25:11.040
partially treated major depressive disorder.

577
00:25:11.040 --> 00:25:14.040
So it's not the antidepressant, it's the underlying disorder

578
00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:16.290
for which the antidepressant was being treated.

579
00:25:16.290 --> 00:25:18.390
And the conclusion of the meta-analysis was

580
00:25:18.390 --> 00:25:23.070
that antidepressants do not cause autism spectrum disorder.

581
00:25:23.070 --> 00:25:24.720
And I don't know if I have to mention it,

582
00:25:24.720 --> 00:25:25.950
but I wanted to call it out.

583
00:25:25.950 --> 00:25:27.420
There is no good evidence

584
00:25:27.420 --> 00:25:30.600
that vaccines cause autism spectrum disorder.

585
00:25:30.600 --> 00:25:32.970
Just felt I had to put that out there, and I did.

586
00:25:32.970 --> 00:25:34.470
Feel good about myself.

587
00:25:34.470 --> 00:25:36.930
All right, from a comorbidity standpoint,

588
00:25:36.930 --> 00:25:38.940
comorbidity is common in patients

589
00:25:38.940 --> 00:25:41.160
with autism spectrum disorder.

590
00:25:41.160 --> 00:25:43.440
ADHD occurs in over 28%.

591
00:25:43.440 --> 00:25:44.880
Almost a third of patients

592
00:25:44.880 --> 00:25:48.210
with autism spectrum disorder will have ADHD.

593
00:25:48.210 --> 00:25:50.820
Intellectual disability is coming close

594
00:25:50.820 --> 00:25:53.520
at about 25% of patients will have a degree

595
00:25:53.520 --> 00:25:55.470
of intellectual disability.

596
00:25:55.470 --> 00:25:58.110
Anxiety disorders and mood disorders,

597
00:25:58.110 --> 00:26:00.270
10 and 11%, respectively.

598
00:26:00.270 --> 00:26:02.670
And then, we get into the more physical things.

599
00:26:02.670 --> 00:26:04.680
This really surprised me in preparing

600
00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:07.290
for this talk is how common epilepsy is.

601
00:26:07.290 --> 00:26:09.750
If you have an intellectual disability

602
00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:14.430
and on an autism spectrum disorder, that's 28% will have,

603
00:26:14.430 --> 00:26:17.070
or excuse me, 21% will have comorbid epilepsy.

604
00:26:17.070 --> 00:26:19.410
If you take away the learning disability

605
00:26:19.410 --> 00:26:21.330
and it's just autism, the number decreases,

606
00:26:21.330 --> 00:26:22.430
but it's still 10 times that

607
00:26:22.430 --> 00:26:24.900
of the general population at 8%.

608
00:26:24.900 --> 00:26:27.690
Really kinda speaking to the genetic component

609
00:26:27.690 --> 00:26:30.270
of autism spectrum.

610
00:26:30.270 --> 00:26:32.940
I remember constipation dealing with a lot of my kids

611
00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:36.390
with autism in clinic was a big issue for them as well.

612
00:26:36.390 --> 00:26:39.600
So asking about constipation

613
00:26:39.600 --> 00:26:41.460
and bowel movements can be very helpful.

614
00:26:41.460 --> 00:26:42.293
And then, as well

615
00:26:42.293 --> 00:26:44.733
as sleep disturbances are amazingly common.

616
00:26:45.690 --> 00:26:49.770
So the American Academy of Pediatrics recommends screening

617
00:26:49.770 --> 00:26:53.250
for autism spectrum disorder.

618
00:26:53.250 --> 00:26:56.403
However, the US Preventive Services Taskforce said, whoa,

619
00:26:57.499 --> 00:27:00.000
there is inadequate or insufficient data

620
00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:01.500
to really recommend screening

621
00:27:01.500 --> 00:27:02.910
for autism spectrum disorder

622
00:27:02.910 --> 00:27:05.340
unless the parents have a concern

623
00:27:05.340 --> 00:27:06.630
or unless the teacher has a concern,

624
00:27:06.630 --> 00:27:10.230
unless the concern of the child having it is raised.

625
00:27:10.230 --> 00:27:11.880
But if you're so moved

626
00:27:11.880 --> 00:27:15.750
to do the screening, there's a tool out there.

627
00:27:15.750 --> 00:27:17.100
It's called M-CHAT.

628
00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:19.860
It's a 20-question questionnaire,

629
00:27:19.860 --> 00:27:21.390
and it's truly a screening.

630
00:27:21.390 --> 00:27:23.550
If somebody scores positive, which is two

631
00:27:23.550 --> 00:27:26.400
or more, you have to do a follow-up assessment

632
00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:28.650
that's pretty detailed.

633
00:27:28.650 --> 00:27:31.380
And that follow-up assessment actually has

634
00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:34.110
pretty impressive sensitivity and specificity.

635
00:27:34.110 --> 00:27:39.110
So my colleagues will end up doing the M-CHAT,

636
00:27:39.180 --> 00:27:41.070
do the follows-up, and if it's positive,

637
00:27:41.070 --> 00:27:45.060
then they're referred to psychology for some testing

638
00:27:45.060 --> 00:27:47.880
because the referral to psychology is really that goal.

639
00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:50.520
It sets the bar for that gold standard

640
00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:52.500
of making the diagnosis.

641
00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:55.020
As the physician who's gotten the history

642
00:27:55.020 --> 00:27:56.190
and interacted with the patient,

643
00:27:56.190 --> 00:27:58.920
you have your clinical judgment about the kid,

644
00:27:58.920 --> 00:28:01.020
whether they have autism spectrum or not.

645
00:28:01.020 --> 00:28:03.733
And then, you have the neuropsychological batteries,

646
00:28:03.733 --> 00:28:07.470
which consist of the psychologist interviewing the parent

647
00:28:07.470 --> 00:28:10.650
on a structured interview, as well as an observation period

648
00:28:10.650 --> 00:28:13.020
in which they observe the child.

649
00:28:13.020 --> 00:28:14.910
The combination of your clinical opinion

650
00:28:14.910 --> 00:28:19.770
as well as the testing really is the diagnosis.

651
00:28:19.770 --> 00:28:24.770
If the kid has autism spectrum,

652
00:28:24.810 --> 00:28:27.030
the American Pediatrics recommends genetic testing.

653
00:28:27.030 --> 00:28:30.030
I refer to a geneticist or I always did.

654
00:28:30.030 --> 00:28:31.860
From an environmental intervention,

655
00:28:31.860 --> 00:28:36.540
the real key here is applied behavioral analytics, ABA.

656
00:28:36.540 --> 00:28:37.380
You've all heard that.

657
00:28:37.380 --> 00:28:38.970
That's kind of operant conditioning

658
00:28:38.970 --> 00:28:43.050
for kids with autism, working both environmentally

659
00:28:43.050 --> 00:28:45.990
to ensure the environment is optimally set up for them

660
00:28:45.990 --> 00:28:49.740
to engage, as well as reinforcing the positive behaviors.

661
00:28:49.740 --> 00:28:52.050
Kid going to school, learning to hang up his coat,

662
00:28:52.050 --> 00:28:53.850
there are signs there to remind him to do it.

663
00:28:53.850 --> 00:28:54.930
And you reward him

664
00:28:54.930 --> 00:28:57.483
in a meaningful way when he does hang up his coat.

665
00:28:58.920 --> 00:29:01.110
What's often forgotten is

666
00:29:01.110 --> 00:29:04.200
when we mainstream these neurodiverse individuals

667
00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:07.350
and they just don't have the same social skillset

668
00:29:07.350 --> 00:29:09.810
as part of the disorder, they can really suffer

669
00:29:09.810 --> 00:29:11.798
in high school and middle school

670
00:29:11.798 --> 00:29:14.850
as they're not being able to engage with their colleagues.

671
00:29:14.850 --> 00:29:16.290
So there are various support groups up

672
00:29:16.290 --> 00:29:19.740
that can do social skills training that can be very helpful.

673
00:29:19.740 --> 00:29:23.310
From pharmacotherapy, there is no pharmacotherapy agent

674
00:29:23.310 --> 00:29:26.670
that's been shown to address the core symptomatology

675
00:29:26.670 --> 00:29:28.380
of autism spectrum disorder.

676
00:29:28.380 --> 00:29:32.520
Our symptoms are meant to address secondary issues,

677
00:29:32.520 --> 00:29:34.500
agitation, aggression.

678
00:29:34.500 --> 00:29:37.050
We have two antipsychotics with FDA approval

679
00:29:37.050 --> 00:29:39.090
that have pretty good effect sizes.

680
00:29:39.090 --> 00:29:41.490
ADHD, very common.

681
00:29:41.490 --> 00:29:42.540
We have the stimulants,

682
00:29:42.540 --> 00:29:44.460
and we have the non-stimulant medications

683
00:29:44.460 --> 00:29:45.420
with some efficacy.

684
00:29:45.420 --> 00:29:48.210
Not as good as if a patient doesn't have autism,

685
00:29:48.210 --> 00:29:49.620
but still fairly good.

686
00:29:49.620 --> 00:29:51.000
They do have more side effects.

687
00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:52.770
They're more sensitive to the stimulants

688
00:29:52.770 --> 00:29:57.240
than a non-autism spectrum patient with ADHD.

689
00:29:57.240 --> 00:29:58.440
What's impressive with this,

690
00:29:58.440 --> 00:30:01.410
and I wasn't aware, is the alpha agonist have a very good

691
00:30:01.410 --> 00:30:03.660
effect size in this patient population.

692
00:30:03.660 --> 00:30:05.490
But still, the literature suggests starting

693
00:30:05.490 --> 00:30:07.050
with a stimulant.

694
00:30:07.050 --> 00:30:08.460
So what's the prognosis?

695
00:30:08.460 --> 00:30:11.640
We're almost done with this here.

696
00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:15.450
So these patients live less independently

697
00:30:15.450 --> 00:30:17.430
or less commonly employed than individuals

698
00:30:17.430 --> 00:30:20.730
without ASD, autism spectrum disorder.

699
00:30:20.730 --> 00:30:24.030
If there's a baseline solid cognitive foundation,

700
00:30:24.030 --> 00:30:27.120
they have better academic achievement, more employment,

701
00:30:27.120 --> 00:30:29.400
more likely to live independently.

702
00:30:29.400 --> 00:30:32.520
However, if you ask their caregivers, they're less likely

703
00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:34.680
to have meaningful friendships.

704
00:30:34.680 --> 00:30:36.390
I don't actually like that last line.

705
00:30:36.390 --> 00:30:39.150
I think it's up to the patient, the one with autism

706
00:30:39.150 --> 00:30:41.340
to tell us if they've had meaningful relationship.

707
00:30:41.340 --> 00:30:45.000
What's to say if what they consider is meaningful or not?

708
00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:46.620
Again, appreciating some degree

709
00:30:46.620 --> 00:30:48.390
of the neurodiversity that we have.

710
00:30:48.390 --> 00:30:49.320
And what was striking

711
00:30:49.320 --> 00:30:52.590
for me in this talk is this increased early mortality,

712
00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:54.960
two times that of the general population.

713
00:30:54.960 --> 00:30:56.160
When they looked further in,

714
00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:58.410
they saw it was related to the epilepsy I mentioned.

715
00:30:58.410 --> 00:31:00.750
That's one of the reasons I included it on the slide,

716
00:31:00.750 --> 00:31:03.150
as well as an increased suicide rate.

717
00:31:03.150 --> 00:31:07.260
The odds rate three times that of non-patients with autism,

718
00:31:07.260 --> 00:31:10.320
which I found very starkly concerning.

719
00:31:10.320 --> 00:31:12.660
So very briefly, obsessive compulsive disorder.

720
00:31:12.660 --> 00:31:14.190
We're almost done here.

721
00:31:14.190 --> 00:31:17.280
It's very simply the presence of obsessions

722
00:31:17.280 --> 00:31:19.140
or compulsions or both.

723
00:31:19.140 --> 00:31:20.910
The most common presentation is they have

724
00:31:20.910 --> 00:31:23.490
both obsessions and compulsions.

725
00:31:23.490 --> 00:31:26.130
These obsessions and compulsions are very time-consuming

726
00:31:26.130 --> 00:31:27.930
or very disturbing to the patient.

727
00:31:27.930 --> 00:31:30.360
Usually, they're both very time-consuming

728
00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:31.410
and very disturbing

729
00:31:31.410 --> 00:31:34.080
to the patient, causing a lot of distress.

730
00:31:34.080 --> 00:31:35.370
So what is an obsession?

731
00:31:35.370 --> 00:31:39.780
An obsession are recurrent thoughts, images, or beliefs.

732
00:31:39.780 --> 00:31:43.860
Sometimes, impulses that cause significant anxiety.

733
00:31:43.860 --> 00:31:47.160
The fear of contamination is a big one.

734
00:31:47.160 --> 00:31:51.930
These thoughts cause significant concern, panic attacks.

735
00:31:51.930 --> 00:31:54.360
And they're not related to schizophrenia

736
00:31:54.360 --> 00:31:57.330
or anything else, but these obsessions,

737
00:31:57.330 --> 00:31:58.980
because they're so distressing,

738
00:31:58.980 --> 00:32:01.530
the patient develops compulsions,

739
00:32:01.530 --> 00:32:05.820
which is a pathological way to calm that anxiety.

740
00:32:05.820 --> 00:32:07.200
So they do the compulsions

741
00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:09.810
to release, decrease that anxiety.

742
00:32:09.810 --> 00:32:12.780
Sometimes, the compulsions are thematically related

743
00:32:12.780 --> 00:32:15.120
to the obsession, i.e., hand washing,

744
00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:17.190
but disproportionate to the risk.

745
00:32:17.190 --> 00:32:19.050
Sometimes, they have absolutely nothing

746
00:32:19.050 --> 00:32:20.587
to do with the compulsion.

747
00:32:20.587 --> 00:32:23.677
"I'm concerned my mother's gonna have a stroke,

748
00:32:23.677 --> 00:32:26.347
"so I'm gonna say three, three times; two twice;

749
00:32:26.347 --> 00:32:29.317
"one once; four, four times; and five, five times every time

750
00:32:29.317 --> 00:32:31.350
"I have that thought and she won't have a stroke."

751
00:32:31.350 --> 00:32:34.080
Not remotely related, but that's the compulsion

752
00:32:34.080 --> 00:32:37.740
that relieves the obsessions and associated anxiety.

753
00:32:37.740 --> 00:32:39.660
These are such the common ones.

754
00:32:39.660 --> 00:32:42.277
My wife would say, "I would add a garage door closure

755
00:32:42.277 --> 00:32:43.407
"on the bottom there."

756
00:32:44.520 --> 00:32:46.170
And then, my compulsion would be the checking

757
00:32:46.170 --> 00:32:48.470
of the garage door closure, having to go back.

758
00:32:49.530 --> 00:32:51.090
It's actually not very prevalent.

759
00:32:51.090 --> 00:32:52.770
One to 2% of the population.

760
00:32:52.770 --> 00:32:54.840
Men and women are equally affected as adults.

761
00:32:54.840 --> 00:32:57.630
But in children, this can be a board question,

762
00:32:57.630 --> 00:33:00.300
males are often more affected than females

763
00:33:00.300 --> 00:33:01.380
at a pretty good clip.

764
00:33:01.380 --> 00:33:04.740
And therefore, there's a lower age of onset

765
00:33:04.740 --> 00:33:06.630
in boys than in girls with this.

766
00:33:06.630 --> 00:33:08.850
And comorbidity with depression is more the rule

767
00:33:08.850 --> 00:33:10.050
than the exception.

768
00:33:10.050 --> 00:33:14.610
And the treatment are antidepressants. They're the SSRIs.

769
00:33:14.610 --> 00:33:17.280
The dose of the SSRI is higher than we use

770
00:33:17.280 --> 00:33:18.540
for depression commonly.

771
00:33:18.540 --> 00:33:21.180
Sertraline is pushed to 150 or 200,

772
00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:24.120
and the typical trial in depression is four to six weeks

773
00:33:24.120 --> 00:33:26.280
before we say if it's gonna work or not.

774
00:33:26.280 --> 00:33:28.800
In OCD, it's 8 to 12 weeks

775
00:33:28.800 --> 00:33:30.660
before it declared a failure or not.

776
00:33:30.660 --> 00:33:33.420
It's a long, high dose type of treatment.

777
00:33:33.420 --> 00:33:36.720
And then, cognitive behavioral therapy is the treatment.

778
00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:39.240
So comorbidity is common

779
00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:43.230
in ADHD, mostly learning disability, remember that.

780
00:33:43.230 --> 00:33:45.540
ADHD must be present in more than one setting

781
00:33:45.540 --> 00:33:48.210
and symptoms present before age 12.

782
00:33:48.210 --> 00:33:52.290
The best treatment is medication management co-occurring

783
00:33:52.290 --> 00:33:53.610
with behavioral modification,

784
00:33:53.610 --> 00:33:56.460
at least in childhood and early adolescence.

785
00:33:56.460 --> 00:33:59.940
And ADD in adults is primarily inattentive

786
00:33:59.940 --> 00:34:01.830
and the high doses for OCD.

787
00:34:01.830 --> 00:34:04.650
Thank you, all. I appreciate you staying a little late.

788
00:34:04.650 --> 00:34:06.773
<v Moderator>Thank you very much, Dr. Heinrich.</v>

789
00:34:07.688 --> 00:34:10.938
(gentle ambient music)

